[[File:Harry Charles Purvis Bell portrait ~1890.jpg|thumb|HCP Bell, c. 1890.]]
'''Harry Charles Purvis Bell''', [[Ceylon Civil Service|CCS]] (21 September 1851 – 6 September 1937), more often known as HCP Bell, was a British civil servant and the first [[Department of Archaeology (Sri Lanka)|Commissioner of Archaeology]] in Ceylon.

==Early life==
Born in [[British India]] in 1851, he was sent to England for his education. 

==Civil service career==
Without going to university, Bell came to Ceylon as a civil officer in the [[Ceylon Civil Service]] and went on to serve as a [[customs officer]]. He thereafter served as a [[District Courts of Sri Lanka|District Judge]]. 

==Archaeology==
Appointed an official archaeologist, in July 1890 the [[Governors of British Ceylon|Governor of Ceylon]], Sir [[Arthur Hamilton-Gordon, 1st Baron Stanmore|Arthur Gordon]], appointed Bell as the first Archaeological Commissioner and Head of the Archaeological Survey of Ceylon.<ref>[http://www.archaeology.gov.lk/history1.html Department of Archaeology - History<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> he carried out many excavations in Ceylon (now [[Sri Lanka]]) for the Archaeological Survey during an appointment running from 1890 to 1912.<ref>Robin W. Winks, Alaine M. Low, ''The Oxford History of the British Empire'' (1999), p. 244.</ref>

After retirement, he also investigated the [[archaeology]] and [[epigraphy]] of the [[Maldives]], where he had been earlier in his life.<ref>[http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/info/include/history_early_travellers.php#], [http://www.cpamedia.com/travel/black_magic_in_paradise/]</ref> and studied the linguistics of the [[Maldivian language]]. Bell had developed a good friendship with the king of the Maldives, who put his own royal [[schooner]] ''Fath-ul-Majid'' at his disposition to carry out archaeological research in certain atolls south of Malé.{{sfn|Romero Frías|2003}}

